social_posts.post_text: I read this out over the air today but figured I should post it here too. I’m real excited about it all, and am so pumped for Elamin too. Scroll to the end for the true gift.

Canadian psychedelic rock band @thesadiesofficial are known for their wild live sets and impressive collaborations with artists such as Neko Case, Neil Young, Gord Downie and Greg Keelor of Blue Rodeo.

In February of this year, lead singer Dallas Good sadly died unexpectedly and this summer, the band released their final recorded album with Dallas titled Colder Streams.

Dallas’s brother and bandmate Travis Good sat down with @tomjoepower along with drummer Mike Belitsky to talk about Dallas’ impact on the Canadian music scene and the future of the band.

Full interview is up now on our YouTube channel! 🔗Link in bio.

Oscar award-winning director @gdtreal’s latest film brings a new perspective to the classic children’s story, Pinocchio. Exploring disobedience as a virtue in his adaptation, del Toro describes using this beloved puppet as a perfect vessel to tackle complex themes.

He joined @tomjoepower in the studio to share more about Pinocchio, why he decided to set the film in Mussolini’s fascist Italy and why he chose to use stop-motion.

Full interview is up now on our YouTube channel! 🔗Link in bio.

Award-winning playwright Trey Anthony (@blackgirlinlove) was surprised by the initial success of @dakinkinmyhair. In celebration of its 20th anniversary, the critically acclaimed play returns for a run in Toronto at the Bluma Appel Theatre.

In 2019, Korean actor Song Kang-Ho charmed audiences all around the world with his performance in the Oscar-award-winning film Parasite. However, regardless of the many prestigious accolades the film received, as he gets older, he sees these career high points simply as dots on the timeline of life’s greater journey. 

He sat down with @tomjoepower to discuss the experience of winning big, his approach to acting and his latest film, Broker. 

The full interview is available now on our YouTube channel. 🔗 Link in bio.

You could say @directorx is an accidental meme pioneer. His music video for Drake’s earworm Hotline Bling held pop culture captive for the better part of 2016 and to this day, the meme format lives on.

He joined @tomjoepower in the studio to discuss his longstanding career as a hip hop cinematic auteur. 

The full interview is available now on our YouTube channel. 🔗 Link in bio.

New logo, new letter, new headshots, new theme, new podcast, new format. It’s a big day here for our team on Q. Our first episode is a conversation with Sam Smith and then one with Shania Twain. I could go on (and I have) but the show today feels like it’s exactly how we want it to sound - and what we’d like you to hear. Do me a favour and click the link in my bio to subscribe/follow. When I was (a slightly disheveled) 29 I got to go to Gordon Lightfoot’s house and talk to him about his music, talk about his life and just spend some time with him. Needless to say I was stressed out but I’ll never forget how kind he was to me, how generous he was with his time, and how he even let me play the twelve string in that second photo. There’s no real words that summarize how important he was for Canadian music. I’m heartbroken he’s gone and so happy he was here.

Today on the show I had the honour of doing the “exit interview” for the great Shelagh Rogers which got me on Facebook trying to find this photo. I am 23 here at a folk music conference hanging out with Shelagh at like 2am. Shelagh was kind, generous and helpful to me since (literally) my first day at the CBC. I’m so grateful for the 43 years CBC got to share Shelagh’s voice and I’m so excited to hear what she is doing with that voice in the future. Congrats buddy and thanks for everything.

I’m just so sad to hear about the loss of Bobby Osborne of the Osborne Bros. The music he made with his brother Sonny is some of the most powerful country music ever made - and not just Rocky Top but Ruby too and Making Plans and…well all of it. I was lucky enough to spend some time a few summers ago talking with Bobby at his home just outside of Nashville. He was 89 and we talked about his time in the Korean War, about Rocky Top, Bill Monroe and Jimmy Martin. He told great stories about the early days of Bluegrass when it was pretty much DIY. It’s been rattling around on a hard drive since then so me and the @thebluegrasssituation folks are gonna work over the next few days to get that chat ready so you can hear it. Honoured to have had the time and love to Boj and the rest of his family.

In the deep dark of the pandemic, in 2021, our band @thedardsnl got a call from our friend Alan Doyle, who told us he was working on a project to honour Newfoundland, greatest songwriter - the late Ron Hynes. We went to Alan’s makeshift studio in the battery and we played all day and night. That project is out today and we are so proud to have backed Alan on his version of the St. John’s Waltz. My hope is that this record leads more people to understanding what a singular songwriter Ron was, and does a little bit to pay tribute to the man who inspired us all. Go listen!

Thinking a lot over the past day or so about this conversation I was lucky enough to have with Matthew Perry. My favourite memory of that night is right before we went on the introduction to his appearance had been going for for a while, and then another while, and then there was a big list of sponsors so we had been waiting in this tiny backstage room for ages and after it kept on going he looked at me and said “I don’t remember a time I wasn’t in this room”. I started laughing and he said “that’s funny - I said that to the other cast in Friends when we were shooting the fountain scene for the opening credits which took all day to shoot -  I said I couldn’t remember a time I wasn’t in that fountain”. The doors opened and we walked out and he talked openly and honestly about his struggles and his life. I’m so sad Matthew has passed on so young and I’m thinking and sending love to all his friends and family.

Heartbroken to hear the news about Charles Officer. You’ll never meet a kinder, warmer, empathetic, passionate man. Brilliant storyteller, excellent filmmaker. Charles would come on the show to talk about his latest project or to talk about the state of the industry in Canada and we got to know each other a little bit that way. Then we would hang a little bit at receptions and galas and all that stuff. But my favourite memory was when I was flying to Montreal and ended up getting sat next to Charles. Our flight was delayed three hours on the tarmac and then we got stuck on the tarmac again when we landed. So all in all about five hours for what should’ve been in 90 minute trip. We chatted the whole time, told stories, talked about hockey, filmmaking, and our families. Looking back now I’m so grateful for that flight delay. (The second slide is from when we FINALLY landed). My deepest love to all who loved him and to his family especially as I know he loved them so deeply.
